about.summary: Full 64-bit resolution date and time support with resolution up to nanosecond granularity is provided, with easy transition to and from the standard 'POSIXct' type.

name: r-nanotime
raw_meta_yaml:
{% set version = '0.2.4' %}

{% set posix = 'm2-' if win else '' %}
{% set native = 'm2w64-' if win else '' %}

package:
  name: r-nanotime
  version: {{ version|replace("-", "_") }}

source:
  url:
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/nanotime_{{ version }}.tar.gz
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/Archive/nanotime/nanotime_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  sha256: 2dfb7e7435fec59634b87563a215467e7793e2711e302749c0533901c74eb184

build:
  merge_build_host: True  # [win]
  # If this is a new build for the same version, increment the build number.
  number: 1
  # no skip

  # This is required to make R link correctly on Linux.
  rpaths:
    - lib/R/lib/
    - lib/

# Suggests: RUnit, data.table, xts
requirements:
  build:
    - {{ posix }}zip               # [win]

  host:
    - r-base
    - r-rcppcctz >=0.2.3
    - r-bit64
    - r-zoo

  run:
    - r-base
    - r-rcppcctz >=0.2.3
    - r-bit64
    - r-zoo

test:
  commands:
    # You can put additional test commands to be run here.
    - $R -e "library('nanotime')"           # [not win]
    - "\"%R%\" -e \"library('nanotime')\""  # [win]

  # You can also put a file called run_test.py, run_test.sh, or run_test.bat
  # in the recipe that will be run at test time.

  # requires:
    # Put any additional test requirements here.

about:
  home: https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=nanotime
  summary: Full 64-bit resolution date and time support with resolution up to nanosecond granularity
    is provided, with easy transition to and from the standard 'POSIXct' type.
  license: GPL2
  license_family: GPL
  license_file:
    - '{{ environ["PREFIX"] }}/lib/R/share/licenses/GPL-2'

extra:
  recipe-maintainers:
    - ihnorton
    - shelnutt2
